items.title: Warbirds in Review Vultee BT-13
items.html:
Vultee BT-13 owned by the Women Air Force Service Pilots (WASP) Museum.

History comes to life through legendary wartime aircraft during Warbirds in Review sessions, which delve into aircraft restoration and operation and spotlight veterans sharing stories about what it was like to fly in combat or provide ground support. Presentations take place at 10 a.m. and 1 p.m. daily, July 24-29 on the Warbirds in Review ramp in Warbird Alley. The schedule also includes daily demonstrations at 9:30 a.m. and 12:30 p.m. from the Warbirds Living History Group on flight gear associated with the upcoming aircraft. Next, vocalist Theresa Eaman will entertain the crowds with tunes from the 1940's through the 1960's. Several Warbirds in Review presentations will be followed by book signing opportunities in the Warbirds Merchandise Building.

“July 2017 marks the 15th Anniversary of Warbirds in Review” said Connie Bowlin, EAA Warbirds of America president and Warbirds in Review program founder. “As I look back on the modest beginning thinking of Tex Hill, Bud Anderson, Robin Olds, Gunther Rall, Shorty Rankin, and so many other World War II, Korea, Vietnam, Gulf War, Afghanistan and current military veterans who have been a part of Warbirds in Review, it is humbling. What began with a simple idea, with a boom box and roll around stairs, to offer a time when people could come to hear an owner talk about their aircraft has become a truly world class program. With David Hartman as the writer and moderator, the award winning production crew of Sleeping Dog Productions, the support of Jim Hagedorn, Scotts Miracle Gro Company, Warbird members Ron and Diane Fagen, numerous other donors and the total support of aircraft owners, pilot and ground crew members, we have grown to a level beyond all expectations. The live streaming of Warbirds in Review in 2016 was viewed in 64 countries.  For me personally it is a little overwhelming to know that we have entertained and shared our history with the world.  With Jumbotron, bleachers, sound systems, worldwide live streaming and the participation of so many terrific Warbird members the evolution has exceeded all expectations.”

BT-13 – WASP – In 1942, as the country reeled from the attack on Pearl Harbor, trained male pilots were in short supply. Qualified pilots were needed to fight the war. Twenty-eight experienced civilian women pilots volunteered to take the job of ferrying aircraft. They formed the country’s first female squadron in late summer 1942. In 2017 the American Aviation Heritage Foundation donated a beautiful, newly restored BT-13 to the WASP museum. This BT-13, from start to finish, was intended for donation to the WASP to be flown in tribute to their service.  That is impressive.

items.title: VFR into IMC: Hope Isn't a Strategy
items.html: Situations deteriorate rapidly when pilots are flying VFR venture into unanticipated IMC conditions. Join AOPA in analyzing an actual accident scenario.  Listen to pilot and air traffic controller communications and join other seminar participants in analyzing decisions and options.  Discuss and share critical decisions, actions, and techniques to avoid what continues to be one of the most treacherous flight profiles.

items.title: Cessna Owner Organization / Piper Owner Society
Time To Climb Record Aircraft Dev.
items.html: Several years ago an American rotary engine aficionado by the name of Russ McFarlane living in New Castle Australia decided to build a Mazda rotary powered world record attempt time to climb aircraft. Russ was a long time subscriber to the Rotary Engine News Letter. The propeller driven absolute time to climb record he assumed was 90 seconds from a dead stop on the runway to 3000 meters. This is about the aircraft and engine development from an engineering perspective.

items.html:
The Oshkosh Transit System provides shuttle buses from downtown and the UW Oshkosh campus to the convention grounds.

Oshkosh Transit System

items.title: Sunday Air Show
items.html:
The world's best aerobatic pilots make Oshkosh a priority for their air show performance schedule because they have the opportunity to strut their stuff in front of their peers in the aerobatic community, as well as perhaps the most aviation-savvy audience on the planet.                     

That's why every afternoon during the convention you'll see scores of faithful fans numbering in the thousands lining the flightline, making sure they have a good viewpoint of their favorite performers.

AirVenture’s daily air shows feature a vast variety in today’s world of flight - precision aerobatics, the latest innovations, rare and unique flying examples, and history coming alive through warbird and vintage showcases.

Sunday, July 30, 2017

Patriot Parachute Demo Team, Mike Goulian (Extra 330SC), Kirby Chambliss (Edge 540), Patty Wagstaff (Extra 300LX), Skip Stewart (Prometheus 2), Matt Chapman (Extra 330LX), Redline Airshows, Greg Shelton and Ashley Key (450 Super Stearman/wing walking), Kyle Franklin (Piper Cub), Maj. Joshua Boudreaux (Wild Blue), Scott Yoak (P-51 Mustang), International Aerobatic Club competition demo (Cameron Jaxheimer), USAF Heritage Flight, Blue Angels (non-aerobatic demo) and Fat Albert

items.title: What You Don't Know About Stalls
items.html: Think you’ve heard it all about stalls?  What’s the most common phase of flight for stall related accidents?  Chances are you guessed wrong.  Join the AOPA Air Safety Institute for an analysis of over 2,000 stall accidents.  View cockpit videos of inadvertent stalls and learn when to really be wary and what to watch for to avoid some of the most dangerous accident sequences in all of aviation.

items.title: NASAs Quiet Supersonic Aircraft
items.html: The NASA Commercial Supersonic Technology (CST) Project has completed a preliminary design for a Low-Boom Flight Demonstration X-plane. The aircraft is designed to generate shock waves that create a soft “thump” rather than the disruptive boom currently associated with supersonic flight. The presentation will summarize the why and how of this project technology, reveal some of the aircraft design features, and discuss the future fabrication of the aircraft.

items.title: Switchblade Prototype Completion
items.html: The full-scale carbon fiber prototype is the result of extensive aeronautical and mechanical engineering, wind tunnel testing, and ground prototype testing. Milestones such as the wings, wing swing mechanism, cabin, eyes forward display, controls, safely features, and tail will be shown – including challenges encountered and solutions found. What are this vehicle’s capabilities? Q & A at end of presentation.

items.title: Composite 101
items.html:
Patterned after the highly successful EAA SportAir Workshops, you'll get hands-on and learn just about every skill you need to build an airplane at daily workshops.

Learn about fiberglass and foam lay-ups and actually construct a composite sandwich structure.

items.title: Hot Topics in Aviation Law
items.html: The Legal Advisory Council and a visiting NTSB judge will address handling FAA inquiries, certificate actions, NTSB hearings, ramp checks, Pilots Bill of Rights, medical reform, and a variety of other subjects of interest to EAA members.

items.title: The Story of the Lady Be Good
How to Avoid a Fighter Escort
Scratch Building with a CNC Router
items.html: Ever wonder if you could "3D print" your own aircraft parts? Now that CNC(Computer Numerical Control) routers are available for less than the price of a 3D printer, you can print your own parts in your garage. We will model a part in CAD, create the tool paths with a CAM tool, and manufacture the part in the workshop. We will explore feeds and speeds for working with aluminum and introduce advanced topics such as tiling to allow you to cut those larger pieces such as aircraft skins.

items.title: Opportunities for Pilots at Horizon
items.html: Horizon Air: behind the name are men and women with a "can-do" spirit and a passion for excellence. It's a heartfelt approach, as much as technological innovations and customer-pleasing onboard service that's at the core of the "Horizon experience."

items.title: IFR Decision Making Chasing Choices
items.html: Processing information and making clear decisions while flying in IMC conditions can be challenging. Join AOPA in analyzing accident scenarios where pilots made questionable decisions, under the stress and confusion that IMC flying can sometimes bring.  What led to the suboptimal decisions?  How can we avoid task-saturation and ensure solid decision making when flying in IMC?

items.title: Guerilla Marketing & Your Business
items.html: Creative, outside-the-box thinking will give you unique opportunities to market your business, beating out other typical startups. This class will include a discussion of the top 10 guerrilla marketing techniques to help your business really “take off.” Learn simple-to-implement methods that are cheap (and often free) that can increase your business potential, and ultimately, your income and business.

items.html: Annual EAA Membership Meeting. Presentation of Chairman’s Award recipient, Maj. Gen. John Miller and Freedom of Flight recipients Chesley “Sully” Sullenberger and Jeff Skiles.

items.title: Engine Blueprinting
items.html: Perhaps a bit of a misnomer, we will attempt to demystify the terminology as to what it is, how it is done, and benefits derived.

items.title: Designing the Perfect Paint Scheme
items.html: Craig will share his perspectives and experience on aircraft paint scheme and vinyl design. The presentation will outline the concepts, thought processes and elements of design for aircraft, highlighting both best practices and potential pitfalls. This presentation will change the way you look at aircraft, and will give you the tools you need to create your own beautiful paint scheme or vinyl design.

items.title: Photography 101
items.html: The forum will cover some basics of lighting, exposure and composition with a focus on aviation photography. This will include shooting airplanes both in flight and static. We will also cover equipment, lens choice, and panning to capture movement.

items.title: Western Michigan University - College of Aviation
Type Club Representatives
items.html: Vintage hosts representatives of many aircraft type clubs. They can answer questions about specific vintage aircraft, such as Aeroncas, Bellancas, Cubs, Cessnas, Navions, Pipers, Wacos and many others.

items.title: How to Avoid a Fighter Escort
Maintaining Proficiency at Home
items.html:
Keeping the rust off your flying skills is sometimes easier said than done. It's not always possible to get out to the airport during a busy week, especially when you also have to fight with questionable weather. Thanks to at home simulation equipment, there are ways to stretch those flying muscles. This presentation will provide practical ideas for both VFR and IFR pilots to maintain proficiency at home. EA6176715

The tricycle-gear Zenith STOL CH 750 "Super Duty" model increases the gross weight of the STOL CH 750 (from 1,320 to 1,900 lbs), adds a rear jump seat (for a total of 3 seats), and introduces the "open cabin" with the Unpanel integrated avionics display from Avilution, maximizing cabin space and visibility by getting rid of the convention instrument panel and replacing it with a single repositionable 17-inch glass panel.  Learn about the design and construction of this new design, as well as available configurations and kits being offered.

items.title: VAA Town Hall Meeting
items.html: At this meeting, VAA leaders will discuss recent activities of the association, current plans, and our goals for the future. We will also answer any questions you may have on the activities of the association, the publications, membership services and the like. We hope to let the membership know as much about the association as possible. Please bring your comments and suggestions to this meeting.  We need to hear your praises and gripes as well.

items.title: Twilight Flight Fest
items.html:
Starting this year at EAA AirVenture Oshkosh 2017, the Twilight Flight Fest at the Fun Fly Zone will consist of a series of flying events on Monday, Tuesday, Thursday, and Friday evening during AirVenture.

After an opening monologue by announcer Jon “Jughead” Counsell, EAA STOL Invitational Flying will begin. STOL flying used to be a part of the main air show schedule at Oshkosh, but moving it to the Fun Fly Zone for two nights last year worked well, because the aircraft were able to take off from their preferred surface of grass and fly when winds were more favorable.

Now the STOL invitational will take place during all four nights of the Twilight Flight Fest, but that’s not all that will be going on at that time. The Paradigm Aerobatic Team will be performing as well, expanding on their successful appearance at Oshkosh last year.

After the STOL flying and Paradigm performance, Twilight Flight Fest still has more left to offer. Guests can expect to see skydiving or other events well suited for the dimming light, demos by fixed wing ultralights and light sport aircraft, gyroplanes, powered parachutes, and 3D RC flying.

The Twilight Flight Fest will provide attendees with an up-close look other forms of aviation, and should offer a fun and fresh perspective to any and all crowd members.

items.title: GTN Pilot Training
items.html:
GTN Pilot Training

Topic: Hands-on Scenario-based Training with Garmin GTN

Location: Hilton Garden Inn on the Oshkosh airfield, 1355 W 20th Ave, Oshkosh, WI 54902

Description: The Garmin Aviation Training team is providing one-day training seminars designed to explain the ins and outs of flight planning and instrument procedures. The course includes real world scenario-based instruction to enhance understanding and promote effective operation of the GTN navigator. Each participant will be provided with their own kiosk housing real Garmin avionics, a training syllabus for in class and at home use, as well as a lunch overlooking the airfield from the hotel patio. Additionally, each participant will receive a $50 credit towards future training opportunities as well as a free 3 month subscription to the Garmin Pilot iOS and Android app.

When: 5 one-day courses – Tuesday - Saturday from 8:30am – 2:30pm (note: 2 more days than last year)

Lunch: Lunch is provided and served on the patio between 11am – 12pm 

Length: Five hours

Cost: $99

Registration: Limited seats are available, registration begins on June 20th on a first come, first serve basis. Reserve your seat by visiting flyGarmin.com and selecting the Training tab. Any remaining seats will be available for reservation on a first come, first serve basis at EAA AirVenture Garmin exhibit Boeing square. All of the seats in 2016 were sold out before the show so we recommend you reserve in advance.

items.title: Renting or Borrowing? Get Insured!
items.html: Jim Anderson and Doug Cox team up to discuss the potential pitfalls of renting or borrowing aircraft without renters/non-owned insurance. Flight instructors, student pilots and pilots flying rented or non-owned aircraft are all at risk. Should an accident occur, you may be held personally liable for thousands or dollars in repair, replacement, legal fees, medical and more. Renters/non-owned insurance offers comprehensive coverage for your protection. Easy to obtain and very affordable!

What Is ADS-B?
items.html: ADS-B, or Automatic Dependent Surveillance-Broadcast, is a cornerstone of NextGen air traffic modernization, and the FAA has mandated that aircraft operating in airspace that now requires a Mode C transponder must be equipped with ADS-B Out by Jan. 1, 2020. We will discuss how ADS-B works, features of ADS-B and what equipment is required to obtain ADS-B "In" and "Out".

items.title: Not a Screw-up by Screwing Up
Automated Export of Engine Data
items.html: Modern general aviation avionics produce valuable data which can be utilized for preventative maintenance. A weakness in the current system is the complex manual process to export the data. When engine data is not exported, it cannot be analyzed in time to prevent an engine malfunction. This presentation will introduce an architecture for automated export of engine data which utilizes low-cost, off-the-shelf, long-range wireless hardware. A live proof-of-concept will be demonstrated.

items.title: Timeless Voices
items.html:
Aviation’s history is made up of many remarkable people, from the best-known aviation personalities to thousands of unheralded people who contributed to the development of aviation in their local communities.

Over the past several years, EAA has been dedicated to collecting their stories in its unmatched aviation oral history project, "Timeless Voices of Aviation."

Under the banner "Let No Story Go Untold," Timeless Voices of Aviation ensures that the first person oral histories of aviation’s development are preserved for future generations of family members, teachers, students, historians and others.

Military aviators, mechanics, air traffic controllers, aircraft designers, builders and restorers, flight instructors, writers, air show performers, administrators, airport and FBO operators, airline employees, and so many more all have unique stories to tell of their aviation lives.

Stop by the the Timeless Voices exhibit in the EAA Aviation Museum and watch some of the "Timeless Voices of Aviation" stories told directly by those who experienced them.

items.title: Bud Anderson - To Fly and Fight
Warbirds in Review P-47 Thunderbolt
items.html:
Republic P-47 Thunderbolt featuring D-Day pilot Deke Holman.

History comes to life through legendary wartime aircraft during Warbirds in Review sessions, which delve into aircraft restoration and operation and spotlight veterans sharing stories about what it was like to fly in combat or provide ground support. Presentations take place at 10 a.m. and 1 p.m. daily, July 24-29 on the Warbirds in Review ramp in Warbird Alley. The schedule also includes daily demonstrations at 9:30 a.m. and 12:30 p.m. from the Warbirds Living History Group on flight gear associated with the upcoming aircraft. Next, vocalist Theresa Eaman will entertain the crowds with tunes from the 1940's through the 1960's. Several Warbirds in Review presentations will be followed by book signing opportunities in the Warbirds Merchandise Building.

“July 2017 marks the 15th Anniversary of Warbirds in Review” said Connie Bowlin, EAA Warbirds of America president and Warbirds in Review program founder. “As I look back on the modest beginning thinking of Tex Hill, Bud Anderson, Robin Olds, Gunther Rall, Shorty Rankin, and so many other World War II, Korea, Vietnam, Gulf War, Afghanistan and current military veterans who have been a part of Warbirds in Review, it is humbling. What began with a simple idea, with a boom box and roll around stairs, to offer a time when people could come to hear an owner talk about their aircraft has become a truly world class program. With David Hartman as the writer and moderator, the award winning production crew of Sleeping Dog Productions, the support of Jim Hagedorn, Scotts Miracle Gro Company, Warbird members Ron and Diane Fagen, numerous other donors and the total support of aircraft owners, pilot and ground crew members, we have grown to a level beyond all expectations. The live streaming of Warbirds in Review in 2016 was viewed in 64 countries.  For me personally it is a little overwhelming to know that we have entertained and shared our history with the world.  With Jumbotron, bleachers, sound systems, worldwide live streaming and the participation of so many terrific Warbird members the evolution has exceeded all expectations.”

P- 47 “Thunderbolt” –  Deke Holman served during World War II as a C-47 copilot on D-Day, later transitioning to the P-47. He retired from United Airlines flying the B-747 so he says he has always flown 47s. The two P-47s that will be on display are owned by John Shoffner and Neal Melton. Deke Holman was part of the air show red shirt team for many years and is a very special friend to many Oshkosh volunteers. It will be fun to recognize Deke’s service while learning about the P-47.

items.title: Aircraft Parking Status
items.html:
Report posted Wednesday, May 3.

General Aviation Camping and Parking Areas

Starting on Friday, July 21st, this web page will report the status of the General Aviation Camping and the General Aviation Parking areas.

Showplane Camping and Parking Areas

Showplane areas accommodate experimentals (homebuilts), warbirds, production aircraft manufactured prior to 1971, ultralights, and amphibians.  These areas are expected to remain open for the duration of AirVenture 2017.

Field Status

This section will be used to report field conditions at Wittman Regional Airport.  Most aircraft will need to taxi on designated turf areas, including temporary grass taxiways.  Volunteer crews will have marked areas not suitable for taxiing aircraft.  As always, pilots should keep a sharp watch for obstructions and traffic cones whenever taxiing off of paved surfaces.

Airport Layout Information

Note that the stub taxiways north of Runway 9/27 have been renumbered.  The 2017 AirVenture NOTAM (page 13) shows the current configuration.  Be sure to have a copy of the 2017 NOTAM with you when you arrive.  A free, printed copy of the NOTAM can be ordered at www.eaa.org/notam. 

Next planned update to this page: July 21st, 2017.  Have a great flight!

items.title: Situational Awareness in IMC
items.html:
It is essential for an instrument pilot to stay ahead of the airplane at all times. It requires awareness of a large variety of elements that go beyond just knowing where one is and what is next. In this seminar, MCFI Doug Stewart will discuss how he employs the many different elements of situational awareness to drive his IFR best practices. EA6176716

items.title: Back-Country Flying with SkyChick
items.html: Ramona Cox “SkyChick’s” fast-paced presentation is for all levels and full of stunning photos and action-packed cockpit videos which put YOU in the pilot’s seat to see, hear and FEEL what it would be like to land at challenging back-country airstrips.  Learn the secrets of when and where to go, gear recommendations and tips covering terrain, density altitude, weather and other key issues. Her exciting real-life drama stories and lessons learned will keep you on the edge of your seat.

items.title: Flight Testing With Your Smartphone

The special focus of this presentation is how to use your smartphone to measure key performance specs of your aircraft, with flight data demos.

items.title: Twilight Flight Fest
items.html:
Starting this year at EAA AirVenture Oshkosh 2017, the Twilight Flight Fest at the Fun Fly Zone will consist of a series of flying events on Monday, Tuesday, Thursday, and Friday evening during AirVenture.

After an opening monologue by announcer Jon “Jughead” Counsell, EAA STOL Invitational Flying will begin. STOL flying used to be a part of the main air show schedule at Oshkosh, but moving it to the Fun Fly Zone for two nights last year worked well, because the aircraft were able to take off from their preferred surface of grass and fly when winds were more favorable.

Now the STOL invitational will take place during all four nights of the Twilight Flight Fest, but that’s not all that will be going on at that time. The Paradigm Aerobatic Team will be performing as well, expanding on their successful appearance at Oshkosh last year.

After the STOL flying and Paradigm performance, Twilight Flight Fest still has more left to offer. Guests can expect to see skydiving or other events well suited for the dimming light, demos by fixed wing ultralights and light sport aircraft, gyroplanes, powered parachutes, and 3D RC flying.

The Twilight Flight Fest will provide attendees with an up-close look other forms of aviation, and should offer a fun and fresh perspective to any and all crowd members.

items.title: GTN Pilot Training
items.html:
GTN Pilot Training

Topic: Hands-on Scenario-based Training with Garmin GTN

Location: Hilton Garden Inn on the Oshkosh airfield, 1355 W 20th Ave, Oshkosh, WI 54902

Description: The Garmin Aviation Training team is providing one-day training seminars designed to explain the ins and outs of flight planning and instrument procedures. The course includes real world scenario-based instruction to enhance understanding and promote effective operation of the GTN navigator. Each participant will be provided with their own kiosk housing real Garmin avionics, a training syllabus for in class and at home use, as well as a lunch overlooking the airfield from the hotel patio. Additionally, each participant will receive a $50 credit towards future training opportunities as well as a free 3 month subscription to the Garmin Pilot iOS and Android app.

When: 5 one-day courses – Tuesday - Saturday from 8:30am – 2:30pm (note: 2 more days than last year)

Lunch: Lunch is provided and served on the patio between 11am – 12pm 

Length: Five hours

Cost: $99

Registration: Limited seats are available, registration begins on June 20th on a first come, first serve basis. Reserve your seat by visiting flyGarmin.com and selecting the Training tab. Any remaining seats will be available for reservation on a first come, first serve basis at EAA AirVenture Garmin exhibit Boeing square. All of the seats in 2016 were sold out before the show so we recommend you reserve in advance.

Pre-Registion Required
Registration Website Information Will Be Posted Soon

Join Scott Strimple and a panel of experienced drone operators for this exclusive, one-day Part 107 Preparation Course at AirVenture 2017! The course will cover all of the pre-requisites for becoming a certified Part 107 commercial sUAS (small drone) operator. After attending this course, you will be better prepared to apply for a commercial drone operator's license and pass the FAA test. Some of the topics to be covered include:

1. Applicable regulations relating to small unmanned aircraft system rating privileges, limitations, and flight operation
2. Airspace classification and operating requirements, and flight restrictions affecting small unmanned aircraft operation
3. Aviation weather sources and effects of weather on small unmanned aircraft performance
4. Emergency procedures
5. Crew resource management
6. Radio communication procedures
7. Aeronautical decision-making and judgment
8. Airport operations
9. Maintenance and pre-flight inspection procedures

items.title: Look Up! Clouds Tell a Story
Monday Air Show
items.html:
The world's best aerobatic pilots make Oshkosh a priority for their air show performance schedule because they have the opportunity to strut their stuff in front of their peers in the aerobatic community, as well as perhaps the most aviation-savvy audience on the planet.                          

That's why every afternoon during the convention you'll see scores of faithful fans numbering in the thousands lining the flightline, making sure they have a good viewpoint of their favorite performers.

AirVenture’s daily air shows feature a vast variety in today’s world of flight - precision aerobatics, the latest innovations, rare and unique flying examples, and history coming alive through warbird and vintage showcases. 

Monday, July 24, 2017

Day: Patriot Parachute Demo Team, Matt Chapman (Extra 330LX), Rob Holland (MX-2), Bill Stein (Edge 540), Twin Tigers Aerobatic Team, Aeroshell Aerobatic Team (T-6 Texans), Greg Shelton and Ashley Key (450 Super Stearman/wing walking), John Klatt (Screamin’ Sasquatch), Kyle Franklin (Piper Cub), David Martin (Bücker Jungmeister), Jerry Kerby (Wild Blue), Bob Carlton (Sub Sonex JSX-2), Warbirds of America arrival show, Seaplane fly-overs, Lindbergh 90th anniversary tribute, Embry-Riddle Aeronautical University E-Spirit of St. Louis, Piper Cub 80th anniversary, Bob Hoover tribute

Evening (Twilight Flight Fest at the Fun Fly Zone): EAA STOL Invitational Flying, Paradigm Aerobatic Team (dynamic maneuvering), Patriot Parachute Demo Team, 3-D RC flying

items.title: EPS Diesel Update
items.html: EPS has invested a decade of research, development and testing on a clean sheet design for an aviation diesel engine in the 320 to 420 horsepower range. The company has integrated a number of significant innovations in the design. This forum will update you certification progress.

items.title: Single Pilot IFR
items.html: Learn how to fly single pilot IFR safely and confidently in the National Airspace System from a CFI(I) and aircraft accident investigator who has seen the good and bad in aviation from all angles. Learn how to prepare for the flight, when to adjust your plan, and when to stay on the ground. Learn from the mistakes of others who have paid the ultimate price while flying single pilot IFR. Find out what your instructor never told you.

items.title: Bolt-On Horsepower for Lycomings
items.html: More power and efficiency for your plane, without changing or upgrading the engine? This is possible with a tuned exhaust system. We will explain the design, construction, maintenance & functions of traditional exhaust systems. Then we will present the theory and design concepts of a tuned exhaust system and how it benefits constant speed & fixed pitch aircraft engines. Information on the installation and retrofit of 11 major certified aircraft models as well as experimental.

items.title: The Switchblade & Flying Car Regs
items.html: Response to increased public interest in this new kid of point-to-point transportation, has recently led more companies to get on the flying car bandwagon. What are the regulations governing flying cars? What regs need to change for vertical takeoff and landing vehicles to be used in cities and towns, from your own driveway? What new infrastructure and technology would be needed? How does the Switchblade fit in with all of this? Q & A at end of presentation.

items.title: Warbirds in Review P-51 Mustang
items.html:
Two Old Crow P-51 Mustangs owned by Jack Roush and Jim Hagedorn, with special presenter World War II triple ace Col. Bud Anderson. 

History comes to life through legendary wartime aircraft during Warbirds in Review sessions, which delve into aircraft restoration and operation and spotlight veterans sharing stories about what it was like to fly in combat or provide ground support. Presentations take place at 10 a.m. and 1 p.m. daily, July 24-29 on the Warbirds in Review ramp in Warbird Alley. The schedule also includes daily demonstrations at 9:30 a.m. and 12:30 p.m. from the Warbirds Living History Group on flight gear associated with the upcoming aircraft. Next, vocalist Theresa Eaman will entertain the crowds with tunes from the 1940's through the 1960's. Several Warbirds in Review presentations will be followed by book signing opportunities in the Warbirds Merchandise Building.

“July 2017 marks the 15th Anniversary of Warbirds in Review” said Connie Bowlin, EAA Warbirds of America president and Warbirds in Review program founder. “As I look back on the modest beginning thinking of Tex Hill, Bud Anderson, Robin Olds, Gunther Rall, Shorty Rankin, and so many other World War II, Korea, Vietnam, Gulf War, Afghanistan and current military veterans who have been a part of Warbirds in Review, it is humbling. What began with a simple idea, with a boom box and roll around stairs, to offer a time when people could come to hear an owner talk about their aircraft has become a truly world class program. With David Hartman as the writer and moderator, the award winning production crew of Sleeping Dog Productions, the support of Jim Hagedorn, Scotts Miracle Gro Company, Warbird members Ron and Diane Fagen, numerous other donors and the total support of aircraft owners, pilot and ground crew members, we have grown to a level beyond all expectations. The live streaming of Warbirds in Review in 2016 was viewed in 64 countries.  For me personally it is a little overwhelming to know that we have entertained and shared our history with the world.  With Jumbotron, bleachers, sound systems, worldwide live streaming and the participation of so many terrific Warbird members the evolution has exceeded all expectations.”

P-51 “Old Crow” – It would be difficult to find a veteran who is more respected and admired than Col C.E. “Bud” Anderson or two aircraft owners who have been more involved in warbird history and preservation than Jack Roush and Jim Hagedorn. Col Anderson is the one veteran who has been a part of Warbirds in Review in all of the 15 years. Welcome back Bud, Jack and Jim – we all love hearing your stories and appreciate you.

items.html: Engine expert Mike Busch A&P/IA explains everything you ever wanted to know about modern digital engine monitor instrumentation: their history, the types of equipment available, and how to use it for routine in-flight monitoring during start, taxi, runup, takeoff, climb, descent and landing. He offers recommended alarm settings, flight-test profiles, and case studies showing how engine monitor data can be invaluable in troubleshooting engine problems.

What you will learn you will be able to apply for practical purposes in your aviation activities. EA6176731

From aviation documentaries, to historical dramas and guilty pleasures, to the moon and beyond, the EAA Fly-In Theater presented by Ford Motor Company will have guests covered at EAA AirVenture Oshkosh 2017. Every night beginning Sunday, July 23, through Saturday, July 29, moviegoers can bring lawn chairs and blankets to the Fly-In Theater and enjoy a film projected on a five-story screen. Located adjacent to Camp Scholler, the Fly-In Theater is reminiscent of the drive-in theaters of the past. Each evening the show begins at approximately 8:30 p.m. (approximately 9:30 p.m. on Wednesday and Saturday to follow the night air shows). Movies will be introduced by aviation icons, celebrities, and more (those details to be announced at a later time).

Be sure to catch the following films:

Sunday, July 23: Flying the Feathered Edge and Mission Control
Monday, July 24: Mission: Impossible - Rogue Nation
Tuesday, July 25: Sully
Wednesday, July 26: 30 Seconds Over Tokyo
Thursday, July 27: Rogue One: A Star Wars Story

items.title: Hand Prop Your Aircraft
items.html:
"Prop it Right and Save a Life”

Greg and Cindy Heckman will demonstrate the Safe and Legal way to hand prop an aircraft engine.  Many Vintage aircraft must be started by hand propping since they may not have an electrical system for starting. In the past several years, we have taught well over a thousand people how to hand prop an aircraft engine safely here at Oshkosh. This program was started by the late Dale Gustafson, a long-time vintage aircraft judge, who saw the need since the emergence of the Sport Pilot License and the newly purchased older airplanes.   We miss Gus since he has Gone West in 2014.

items.title: Last Man Club
items.html:
A WW2 veteran destined for life in a retirement home escapes his difficult family situation and embarks on a cross country adventure to find the last remaining members of his B-17 bomber crew with the help of a beautiful accomplice.

Director:

 Bo Brinkman

Writer:

 Bo Brinkman

items.title: Hybrid Electric Aircraft Propulsion
items.html: The next frontier in both large and small aircraft is electrically enhanced propulsion. NASA is developing a new class of power, propulsion, airframe, and thermal technologies that enable quieter, cleaner, and more efficient aircraft that can support new flight applications such as on-demand mobility, regional airport utilization, and enable efficient large transport vehicles. This presentation will provide an overview of how this technology will affect the future of air travel.

items.title: General Camping Guidelines
items.html:
View PDF of Full Guidlines


Credentials

  • You must be an EAA member to purchase a campsite. Only one campsite per member. All water/electric hookups are on a first-paid, first served basis. Secure your site by going online at EAA.org. These sites cannot be secured over the phone.
  • Camping credentials are not valid in EAA Public Parking Lots.
  • Camping credentials must be properly displayed on both on your camping unit and transient vehicle.
  • Any roped off unoccupied site without proper credentials will be removed.

Campsite Size

  • Individual campsites are approximately 20 feet x 30 feet in size and are available for both RV/vehicle and tent camping. 
  • Only one tent or camper and one vehicle per 20 feet x 30 feet campsite are allowed. Larger RVs will be accommodated at the standard daily camping rates.
  • Camping units must be a minimum of 10 feet apart.
  • All camping units and vehicles must be located behind the fire lanes.
  • Additional vehicle and visitor parking passes for a special lot (S Lot) may be purchased at S Lot or Camper Registration.

Generators

  • Generators may be used for electricity, but no engine-driven generators will be operated between the hours of 10:30 p.m. and 6:30 a.m. (except in designated 24-hour use areas).
  • All camping units in 24-hour auxiliary power area must be positioned perpendicular to fire lanes. Fire lanes are marked as burn lines in the grass or with signage.
  • No tents are allowed in the 24-hour auxiliary power area.

Handicap Access

  • A RV/Handicap camping area for those requiring 24-hour operation of auxiliary generators is available.
  • Handicap accessible restrooms are available at three campground shower facilities.
  • A handicap accessible bus that circulates throughout the campground.

Courtesy

  • Courtesy quiet time begins at 10:30 p.m.
  • Please leave campsites the way you found them (fill in any holes from campfires, etc.) and place all waste in appropriate receptacles.
  • Campsites purchased to place non-camping units (i.e. a central meeting location) must be used in a way that supports only those camping in Camp Scholler
  • Events that require catering, security, or hosted alcohol, and/or are by invitation to the general public are not permitted

Campfires & Firewood

In an effort to reduce the risk of emerald ash borer introduction and spread in Wisconsin, the Wisconsin Department of Natural Resources asks that all campground firewood be left at home and purchased near your campsite location. Firewood should be obtained within 10 miles of where you plan to use it. Fines for transporting firewood across state lines are heavily enforced.

  • Firewood is available for purchase at the campground stores and local convenience stores.
  • Do not leave campsite areas without completely extinguishing campfires.
  • No flying objects; i.e. radio controlled aircraft, Chinese lanterns, drones etc.

Personal Transportation

  • Do not operate any unlicensed motorized vehicles including motorbikes, motor scooters, or motorcycles.
  • No roller-skating, skateboarding or rollerblading or hoverboards are allowed.
  • A driver’s license is required to drive any type of vehicle in Camp Scholler.
  • Bicycles and personal transportation devices, such as Segways, are allowed in Camp Scholler only (except that the following are allowed everywhere on the EAA grounds: a. One person electric/handicapped convenience vehicles; and b. Other Personal Disability Mobility Devices, such as Segways, when required because of the individual’s mobility disability and when operated in a safe manner, consistent with 28 C.F.R. 36.311(b)(1).).
  • Bicycle corrals are located in three locations: Theater in the Woods (near the East Gate), Bus Park, and North 40 Gate. 

Pets

AirVenture is not a safe environment for animals due to the heightened sights and sounds. When possible, finding safer arrangements for your pet is highly recommended; however, if you decide to bring your pet, please follow these guidelines for everyone’s enjoyment and safety:

  • Pet camping is available in Camp Scholler only.
  • Pets left unattended must be kept in well ventilated camping unit.
  • Pets must be on a lead at all times.
  • Leads may not be longer than 8 feet.
  • Clean up after your pet.
  • No pets are allowed on the AirVenture convention site.
  • Pets found loose will be turned over to the Oshkosh Police Department.
  • Campers are subject to relocation or expulsion should staff receive complaints due to excessive pet noise or any other pet guideline violation.

Refund Procedures

Refunds are issued as you exit the campground in your vehicle or aircraft. Refunds may be processed at Camp Scholler Camper Registration, South Gate (located at Stits & Ripple roads), and North 40 Registration.

  • Camping credentials must be surrendered to receive a refund.
  • You will be refunded unused days, less the three-day minimum.
  • No refunds are issued on Camp Scholler electric & water campsites.
  • Checkout is 12 p.m. daily. Campers leaving after 12 p.m. will be charged for that day. There is no grace period.

items.title: Homebuilts
items.html:
The world of homebuilt aircraft - officially known in the United States as Experimental Amateur-Built Aircraft - has existed as long as powered flight. Even the Wright brothers were homebuilders, since they didn’t rely on a factory to construct their airplanes. They, like the homebuilders of today, used their own abilities and craftsmanship to construct safe and efficient flying machines.

Today, tens of thousands of homebuilt aircraft fly throughout the world. A significant number of homebuilt aircraft have flown around the globe and one, the Voyager in 1986, was the first airplane ever to fly around the world non-stop on a single tank of fuel.

EAA was founded in 1953 by a group of airplane enthusiasts mostly comprised of airplane builders, although anyone with an aviation interest has always been welcome in the organization. EAA has been the organization of record as the homebuilt movement moved from simple, single-place tube-and-fabric airplanes 60 years ago to today's wide spectrum of aircraft that feature plans- and kit-built models. No matter the airplane project, one thing remains constant – homebuilt aircraft provide a path where nearly anyone can pursue their personal dream of flight.

EAA's extensive resources, available through the EAA members' area or the association's staff, can help any aircraft builder or restorer to create a safe, efficient aircraft that provides recreation and education.

items.title: What You Don't Know Can Hurt You
items.html:
The NTSB states that Loss of Control In-flight (LOC-I) is the greatest cause of fatalities in every sector of aviation. Existing FAA pilot licensing requirements do not require a demonstration of proficiency beyond 60 degrees of bank, and recovery only from rudimentary stalls, or approach to stalls. Unexpected upsets encountered in actual accidents can require pilot skills beyond standard licensing capabilities, which is why international authorities have recommended Upset Prevention and Recovery Training (UPRT) prior to commercial licensing for all pilots worldwide. Find out what comprehensive UPRT entails, what it will teach you that standard licensing training will not, and how it can make you a safer and more confident pilot on every flight you make. EA6176721

https://www.faasafety.gov/SPANS/event_details.aspx?eid=76721&caller=/SPANS/events/ModifyEventList.aspx?type=1

items.title: Scratch Building with a CNC Router
items.html: Ever wonder if you could "3D print" your own aircraft parts? Now that CNC(Computer Numerical Control) routers are available for less than the price of a 3D printer, you can print your own parts in your garage. We will model a part in CAD, create the tool paths with a CAM tool, and manufacture the part in the workshop. We will explore feeds and speeds for working with aluminum and introduce advanced topics such as tiling to allow you to cut those larger pieces such as aircraft skins.

items.title: Aircraft Camping
items.html:
Flying in to Oshkosh and pitching a tent under the wing of your airplane is perhaps the ultimate way to experience AirVenture.

You must be an EAA member to camp in an aircraft camping area. No pre-registration is necessary and airplane campsites are allocated on a first-come, first-served basis (three-day minimum).

Aircraft camping areas on the EAA AirVenture grounds are segmented into two categories:

  • General aircraft camping area (commonly known as the “North 40”)
  • Showplane camping (Vintage, Homebuilt, Ultralight, Rotorcraft and Seaplane categories)

Note that these areas may close temporarily during AirVenture due to aircraft saturation.  The volume of departing aircraft is being watched carefully to see how many more arrivals can be allowed.  If closures are necessary, they will be reported here and also on the AirVenture Arrival ATIS (125.9 and 866-493-5553) and the aircraft parking status telephone recording (920-230-7820). Be sure to plan for an alternate airport, such as Fond du Lac or Appleton.  Transportation to Oshkosh is available from both airports.  Camping is not allowed at Appleton, but Fond du Lac has camping facilities.

Shower facilities, free public Wi-Fi, on-site transportation, and access to food and supplies are available.

items.title: Mastering Crosswinds
items.html:
Crosswind landings are the number one real-world weather-related cause of accidents in general aviation.  Richard Collins said they are the hardest thing to learn in aviation.  Naturally many pilots are apprehensive and lack confidence in crosswind conditions. The Mastering Crosswinds seminar demystifies the crosswind dilemma by looking at the different components.  First, we frame the crosswind problem.  Then we look at the aerodynamics relevant to crosswind operations.  Finally, we discuss crosswind operations, including taxi, takeoff, and landing.  It gives the pilot a better understanding and provides the basis for increased skill and confidence. EA6176719

https://www.faasafety.gov/SPANS/event_details.aspx?eid=76719&caller=/SPANS/events/ModifyEventList.aspx?type=1

items.title: Warbirds in Review F-89 Scorpion
items.html:
Northrop F-89 Scorpion presented by Dick Rutan. 

History comes to life through legendary wartime aircraft during Warbirds in Review sessions, which delve into aircraft restoration and operation and spotlight veterans sharing stories about what it was like to fly in combat or provide ground support. Presentations take place at 10 a.m. and 1 p.m. daily, July 24-29 on the Warbirds in Review ramp in Warbird Alley. The schedule also includes daily demonstrations at 9:30 a.m. and 12:30 p.m. from the Warbirds Living History Group on flight gear associated with the upcoming aircraft. Next, vocalist Theresa Eaman will entertain the crowds with tunes from the 1940's through the 1960's. Several Warbirds in Review presentations will be followed by book signing opportunities in the Warbirds Merchandise Building.

“July 2017 marks the 15th Anniversary of Warbirds in Review” said Connie Bowlin, EAA Warbirds of America president and Warbirds in Review program founder. “As I look back on the modest beginning thinking of Tex Hill, Bud Anderson, Robin Olds, Gunther Rall, Shorty Rankin, and so many other World War II, Korea, Vietnam, Gulf War, Afghanistan and current military veterans who have been a part of Warbirds in Review, it is humbling. What began with a simple idea, with a boom box and roll around stairs, to offer a time when people could come to hear an owner talk about their aircraft has become a truly world class program. With David Hartman as the writer and moderator, the award winning production crew of Sleeping Dog Productions, the support of Jim Hagedorn, Scotts Miracle Gro Company, Warbird members Ron and Diane Fagen, numerous other donors and the total support of aircraft owners, pilot and ground crew members, we have grown to a level beyond all expectations. The live streaming of Warbirds in Review in 2016 was viewed in 64 countries.  For me personally it is a little overwhelming to know that we have entertained and shared our history with the world.  With Jumbotron, bleachers, sound systems, worldwide live streaming and the participation of so many terrific Warbird members the evolution has exceeded all expectations.”

F-89 – Dick Rutan – The F-89 was deployed over much of the northern hemisphere, including USAF bases in Iceland, Greenland, and the continental US. This unsung hero of the Cold War served as the first line of defense against the Soviet bomber threat for many years, until replaced by aircraft such as the F-102 and F-106 in the 1960s. Given Dick’s enthusiasm and charismatic speaking style, this is sure to be one of the highlights of this year’s schedule.

items.title: How Healthy is Your Engine?
items.html: Mike Busch A&P/IA discusses modern methods for monitoring the condition of your piston aircraft engine, including borescope inspection, digital engine monitors, spectrographic oil analysis, and scanning electron microscopy. He also discusses the strengths and weaknesses of two old standbys: compression testing and oil filter inspection. Used together, these tools let us make better decisions and often continue well past TBO with confidence.

items.title: Fire Prevention
items.html:
The Oshkosh Fire Department strictly prohibits wood campfires and charcoal grills (per National Fire Protection Association standards) anywhere in the aircraft camping areas.

Use of white gas or propane-fired camp stoves is allowed in aircraft camping, provided they are used in an area well away from parked aircraft and that the stove is attended at all times. It is strongly recommended that aircraft near the stove be checked for any fuel fumes or leakage, and the stove be elevated above ground level.

items.title: Flying To Burning Man
items.html: Learn about flying to the Burning Man Festival in BlackRock City, Nevada. Ramona Cox, SkyChick, has flown in for the past 20 years and will use stunning photos and videos to show what it is, how to get there, fun activities, AND explain FAA “requirements” for landing. Landing videos, setting up camp, gear recommendations, insurance considerations, protecting your aircraft from the elements and aviation safety tips specific to the environment will be shared and provided in hand-outs.

items.title: How to Get Into the Drone Hobby
Fatigue: When Metal Lets Us Down
items.html: If an engine, propeller or airframe fails catastrophically in flight, chances are the culprit is metal fatigue. Such failures are rare but they can be extremely serious and sometimes life-threatening. What exactly causes metal fatigue, and how can we protect against it? Mike Busch A&P/IA explains the metallurgical basis of fatigue failures, and the factors that aggravate and mitigate it.

items.html:

items.title: Tuesday Air Show
items.html:
The world's best aerobatic pilots make Oshkosh a priority for their air show performance schedule because they have the opportunity to strut their stuff in front of their peers in the aerobatic community, as well as perhaps the most aviation-savvy audience on the planet.                          

That's why every afternoon during the convention you'll see scores of faithful fans numbering in the thousands lining the flightline, making sure they have a good viewpoint of their favorite performers.

AirVenture’s daily air shows feature a vast variety in today’s world of flight - precision aerobatics, the latest innovations, rare and unique flying examples, and history coming alive through warbird and vintage showcases.

items.title: Concert - Barenaked Ladies
items.html:
Ed Robertson, the lead singer of the multi-platinum band Barenaked Ladies, distinctly remembers when he discovered he wanted to be a pilot.

“My uncle flew a (Cessna) 185 on straight floats,” he said. “He took my older brother and I fishing once … I was hooked.”

The now-avid pilot will get to combine his passions of flying and music at EAA AirVenture Oshkosh 2017 as Robertson and the band will headline the always-anticipated opening night concert on Monday, July 24, immediately following the afternoon air show. The concert is once again presented by Ford Motor Company.

After his first flight, Robertson’s aviation dream sat for a while until his wife gave him a ground school course as a 30th birthday gift. Now, flying is as important in his life as music.

“What really appeals to me is the precision of it, the learning and the intellectual demands,” said Robertson, who flew a Cessna 206 amphibian for many years before selling it and now flies a G-1000 Cessna 182 on wheels. “It’s fun and challenging to push yourself to learn new things. I’m in a rock band so my entire adult life has been focused on creativity. Pushing myself to do my instrument rating was really satisfying.”

And then, of course, there’s the cool stuff about flying. Robertson has worked extensively with the Canadian military and even acted as an Honorary Colonel for 424 Squadron Search and Rescue. That’s allowed him to pilot C-130s, Hornets, and even Gryphons (although he admits he’s “a terrible rotary pilot”).

Floatplane flying, though, is where Robertson finds true joy.

“The flexibility and rugged beauty of float flying is like nothing else,” the Canadian-born singer said. “Outside of Toronto, you don’t have to go very far at all to where it may as well be 1930. It’s just lakes and rocks and trees forever. It’s truly a beautiful experience to fly up there.”

Barenaked Ladies bring a set to Oshkosh that is well-known, fun, and infectious. Among the band’s biggest hits are “One Week,” which reached No. 1 on the U.S. Billboard chart, as well as instantly recognizable hits such as “If I Had $1,000,000” and “Pinch Me.” The group has received numerous Billboard Music Awards, Grammy nominations and Juno Awards (Canada’s equivalent of the Grammys). One of the band’s most recognized songs is the theme song from the top-rated CBS comedy “The Big Bang Theory.”

“Ford is proud to be a partner with EAA and we try to bring memorable experiences to the visitors at AirVenture,” said Edsel B. Ford II, member of the Ford Motor Company board of directors. “Since 2006, Ford has been proud to bring top-notch entertainment to AirVenture and provide fun for everyone who joins us at Oshkosh. We’re very much looking forward to the great hits of Barenaked Ladies on opening night!”

Just as with pilot and singer Dierks Bentley, who played the AirVenture opening night concert in 2015, aviation will have a special connection when Robertson and Barenaked Ladies take the stage on July 24. It’s a one-of-a-kind Oshkosh moment for the singer.

“It means I’ll finally be able to make it to the show!” Robertson said. “I’m always working during AirVenture. I look forward to taking it all in. Happy flying, everybody, and keep the dirty side down!”

items.title: Switchblade Materials/Construction
items.html: Carbon fiber is seen as the ultimate in lightweight aircraft construction, yet has a typically slow part production process with high cost. Find out how Samson solves this problem, and can now build at higher production rates, and at lower costs, while maintaining the strength of typical carbon fiber parts. How does this affect the overall cost of vehicle production, and what benefits can be gained? Q & A at end of presentation.

items.title: Buy That Plane...or Walk Away?
items.html: You’re interested in buying an airplane, but it has some issues. Maybe it has an unusually high-time airframe, or an engine that’s near or past TBO, or outdated avionics, or worn paint or interior, or has some mechanical issues that were picked up during the prebuy examination. How do you decide whether to buy the plane or walk away from the deal. Mike Busch A&P/IA walks you though that decision process.

items.title: EAA AirVenture Runway 5K
items.html:
13th Annual AirVenture Runway 5K

Experience what becomes the world's busiest airport from a unique perspective. Whether this is your first or thirteenth Runway 5K, this charity run/walk is a great way to kick start your day! This year, the Runway 5K is held on Saturday, July 29 during AirVenture Oshkosh 2017. The race kicks off at 7:00 a.m. at the Ultralight Barn and encourages everyone, including walkers, first-time runners, and seasoned athletes, to participate.

The course takes you through a tour of the AirVenture campus. You’ll gallop past incredible aircraft that have traveled the world, smell breakfast cooking at our various food stands, and get a preview of aviation exhibits of all types.

You do not need an AirVenture pass to participate in the race, but we invite you to stay the entirety of the day and explore everything that AirVenture has to offer. Shower facilities are available on our grounds. Gear Check closes at 9:30am. If anything at Gear Check is left behind after that time, they will be given to the main Lost & Found, which is located behind the Sky Shoppe.

Registration includes an official event T-shirt, post-race food and refreshments, and an opportunity to purchase discounted admission to AirVenture on race day.  Please note that T-shirt size is NOT guaranteed for those who register after June 30, 2017. 

*Early bird pricing ends on June 30, 2017 at midnight!*

From aviation documentaries, to historical dramas and guilty pleasures, to the moon and beyond, the EAA Fly-In Theater presented by Ford Motor Company will have guests covered at EAA AirVenture Oshkosh 2017. Every night beginning Sunday, July 23, through Saturday, July 29, moviegoers can bring lawn chairs and blankets to the Fly-In Theater and enjoy a film projected on a five-story screen. Located adjacent to Camp Scholler, the Fly-In Theater is reminiscent of the drive-in theaters of the past. Each evening the show begins at approximately 8:30 p.m. (approximately 9:30 p.m. on Wednesday and Saturday to follow the night air shows). items.title: Obstacle Departure Procedures
items.html:
You are preparing to depart into a low overcast from an unfamiliar airport when Center asks “November 1234 Fox, can you maintain your own terrain and obstacle clearance through 6700?” If you aren’t sure how to answer, you are not alone. Many IFR pilots have a poor understanding of the requirements, procedures and best practices necessary to confidently plan an instrument departure particularly when there are obstacle departure procedures published. In this seminar, we will show you how to do this confidently and safely. By reviewing scenarios and examples of challenging departures, you will learn about diverse departures, ODPs, SIDS and more. We’ll also discuss how to anticipate and deal with emergencies that might arise in the early phase of an instrument flight. EA6176720

https://www.faasafety.gov/SPANS/event_details.aspx?eid=76720&caller=/SPANS/events/ModifyEventList.aspx?type=1

items.title: The Switchblade & Flying Car Regs
items.html: Response to increased public interest in this new kid of point-to-point transportation, has recently led more companies to get on the flying car bandwagon. What are the regulations governing flying cars? What regs need to change for vertical takeoff and landing vehicles to be used in cities and towns, from your own driveway? What new infrastructure and technology would be needed? How does the Switchblade fit in with all of this? Q & A at end of presentation.

items.title: F-35 Flight Test Update
items.html: The F-35 now has a 1.6M and 9g envelope, but started with much less. Expanding that envelope has included exciting out-of-control test flying as well as low altitude, high speed, high g rolls. To fly safely into conditions never before seen by a new aircraft takes methodical planning and careful execution. This presentation discusses some of the interesting testing and how risk was minimized.

items.title: Women In Space - Redefining Glamour
items.html:
Meet the women of today’s space programs, including a former NASA astronaut, who are redefining glamour through the exciting, compelling work they are performing expanding our universe, opening our world – building tomorrow’s space travel capabilities to make us earth-independent.

 

·         Moderator: Sandy Coleman – Sandy is the Staff Vice President of NASA Programs for Orbital ATK Washington Operations.  She joined Orbital ATK in 2006 and leads the business development DC activities related to NASA with specific emphasis on the Exploration Program. She is a 40-year veteran of NASA where she was manager of the Space Shuttle External Tank (ET) Project after the Columbia accident responsible for overall management of the redesign, development, production, test, integration, and flight of the ET. 

 Panel Includes:

·         Janet Kavandi, Ph.D. – Dr. Kavandi is a three-time space shuttle astronaut – flying the final mission to the Space Station MIR, mapping the Earth on the Shuttle Radar Topography Mission, and installing the Quest airlock on the International Space Station.  She served as Director of Flight Crew Operations at NASA Johnson and as the Deputy Director of Health and Human Performance. She is now the Director of the NASA Glenn Research Center in Cleveland, Ohio.

·         Shyla Quinn – Shyla is a project engineer for Orbital ATK. In her 11 years with the company she has worked a variety of roles supporting the development and testing of the rocket booster for NASA’s Space Launch System. She was in charge of the cold and heated conditioning for DM-2 and DM-3 static tests. She earned a master’s degree in mechanical engineering. Shyla wants to become an astronaut and loves working with the space program that will get us back to the Moon, to Mars and beyond.

·         Sheila Sharp – Sheila lead the Boeing Launch Vehicle Integration team that helped to design the NASA Space Launch System core and upper stages, and continues to support as a Boeing Defense & Space Mission Assurance director.

·         Michelle Butzke - Michelle has enjoyed a 23-year career in aerospace and works for Lockheed Martin on NASA’s Orion Program. She supports the Program Office and NASA in a liaison role between engineering teams and industry suppliers. She manages the Orion Small Business Plan and is considered an industry expert in Small Business utilization. In 2011 she received NASA’s Space Flight Awareness Silver Snoopy Award. She’s a wife and mother, and has an affinity for flying machines, especially warbirds.

items.title: Aerobatics
items.html:
Are you bored with 'straight-and-level'? Do you think you might be happier upside down? If so, then you’ll want to check out the International Aerobatic Club, the EAA division dedicated to promoting and enhancing the safety and enjoyment of aerobatics.

Loops, rolls, hammerheads, and lomcevaks — these aren’t stunts, but examples of precision flying at its finest, and most fun! IAC members are passionate about this kind of flying, and dedicated to safely enjoying aerobatics in a spirit of fair play and sportsmanship. IAC chapters throughout the U.S. promote aerobatics at a local level and host aerobatic critiques, seminars, and competitions.

Whether you fly aerobatics for fun or in competition, or if you want to, or even if you simply like to watch, we invite you to consider adding the International Aerobatic Club to your EAA membership.

items.title: Ultralights
items.html:
Ultralight flying represents one of the fastest and purest ways to experience the joys of aviation. From powered-parachutes and trikes to traditional fixed wings and even amphibians and rotorcraft, ultralights are fun, exciting, and in most cases, remarkably affordable. Flying ultralights is not a step up or down, but a step into a completely different and exciting sector of the flying community.

In the U.S., flying an ultralight doesn't require a license or a medical certificate of any kind, providing the aircraft meets the Federal Aviation Regulation called Part 103. Part 103 defines an ultralight as an aircraft that meets the following criteria:

Seats

1

Max. Empty Weight (Powered Aircraft)

254 lbs

Max. Empty Weight (Unpowered Aircraft)

155 lbs

Max. Fuel Capacity

5 Gallons

Max. Speed @ Full Power

55 knots

Max. Stall Speed (Power Off)

24 knots

If the aircraft has more than 1-seat or exceeds any of the above criteria, is not an ultralight, and thus not eligible for operation under Part 103.

These are the legal rules by which we fly; they are the most lenient in the world. These privileges, however, carry responsibilities: while there are no specific legal requirements, ultralight pilotsmust be trained just like any other pilot.

items.title: The Bell X-1 & NACA 1946-1958
items.html: The Bell X-1 rocket-powered research aircraft "Glamorous Glennis" piloted by Capt. Yeager is best known for making first supersonic flight, 60 years ago October 14, 1947. The bullet-shaped X-1, built by Bell Aircraft Co., Buffalo, N.Y. for the U.S. Army Air Forces and the NACA, was the first in a successful series of experimental "X-Planes". In all, 5 versions of the X-1 flew at the NACA High-Speed Flight Research Station, Edwards, CA from 1946 to 1958.

items.title: Warbirds in Review A-20 Havoc
items.html:
Douglas A-20 Havoc owned by Lewis Air Legends. 

History comes to life through legendary wartime aircraft during Warbirds in Review sessions, which delve into aircraft restoration and operation and spotlight veterans sharing stories about what it was like to fly in combat or provide ground support. Presentations take place at 10 a.m. and 1 p.m. daily, July 24-29 on the Warbirds in Review ramp in Warbird Alley. The schedule also includes daily demonstrations at 9:30 a.m. and 12:30 p.m. from the Warbirds Living History Group on flight gear associated with the upcoming aircraft. Next, vocalist Theresa Eaman will entertain the crowds with tunes from the 1940's through the 1960's. Several Warbirds in Review presentations will be followed by book signing opportunities in the Warbirds Merchandise Building.

“July 2017 marks the 15th Anniversary of Warbirds in Review” said Connie Bowlin, EAA Warbirds of America president and Warbirds in Review program founder. “As I look back on the modest beginning thinking of Tex Hill, Bud Anderson, Robin Olds, Gunther Rall, Shorty Rankin, and so many other World War II, Korea, Vietnam, Gulf War, Afghanistan and current military veterans who have been a part of Warbirds in Review, it is humbling. What began with a simple idea, with a boom box and roll around stairs, to offer a time when people could come to hear an owner talk about their aircraft has become a truly world class program. With David Hartman as the writer and moderator, the award winning production crew of Sleeping Dog Productions, the support of Jim Hagedorn, Scotts Miracle Gro Company, Warbird members Ron and Diane Fagen, numerous other donors and the total support of aircraft owners, pilot and ground crew members, we have grown to a level beyond all expectations. The live streaming of Warbirds in Review in 2016 was viewed in 64 countries.  For me personally it is a little overwhelming to know that we have entertained and shared our history with the world.  With Jumbotron, bleachers, sound systems, worldwide live streaming and the participation of so many terrific Warbird members the evolution has exceeded all expectations.”

A-20 – Lewis Air Legends, Rod Lewis – On 15 July, 2015, test pilot Stewart “Stew” Dawson gently pulled back on the control yoke and made aviation history as a Douglas A-20 Havoc took to the air for the first time in nearly a quarter-century. Impeccably restored by Aero Trader at Chino Airport, California, the aircraft is A-20G 43-21709. When the A-20 arrived in Oshkosh mid May 2017 we had a good laugh with Stew – it was either the last Warbird to arrive for Airventure 2016 or the first to arrive for 2017. It is a pleasure to, once again, welcome Rod Lewis and thank him for his commitment to the preservation of so many wonderful warbirds.

items.title: The EGT Myth
items.html: The proliferation of digital engine monitors in recent years has caused many pilots to become obsessed with exhaust gas temperature (EGT). Misconceptions abound concerning what EGT means (and doesn't) and how it should be used (and shouldn't). Engine expert expert Mike Busch A&P/IA shows you what EGT actually measures, what it means, and how to use it. He also explains why pilots should really be obsessive about CHT, not EGT.

items.title: General Disability Information
items.html:
Welcome
EAA is dedicated to providing access and services to guests with disabilities in an effort to guarantee that every guest has a safe, comfortable, and enjoyable experience at EAA AirVenture Oshkosh™ 2016. ADA access is available to all AirVenture venues, including the EAA AirVenture Museum.

For more information regarding event access and services, please call (800) 564-6322 or e-mail membership@eaa.org.

Parking
ADA accessible on-site parking is available, and is first come, first served. Your parking identification (DIS ID) permit will be required.

Camping
Located adjacent to the convention grounds, Camp Scholler has designated camping areas for guests with disabilities, as well as 24-hour generator needs. A limited number of sites with electric and water hookups are available to all event guests for an additional fee. Sites are allocated on a first-come, first-served basis. At least one person in each camping unit must be an EAA member. Memberships are available at the Camp Scholler entrance.

Aircraft Parking and Camping
Please display a disabled sign along with the arrival sign (found in the EAA AirVenture Oshkosh 2016 NOTAM) upon your arrival so ground personnel can direct you to the appropriate area. Designated aircraft camping accommodations for guests with disabilities are available in the North 40 as well as the homebuilt camping area.

Bus and Tram Routes
Every on-site bus and tram route throughout the EAA grounds including Camp Scholler, convention grounds, and aircraft parking has at least one ADA accessible vehicle that accommodates various types of wheelchairs and electric conveyance vehicles (ECVs).

Translation Services
EAA's International Visitors Tent offers assistance from friendly volunteers and a place to relax during all the activities. At the International Visitors Tent, guests receive information about AirVenture or the surrounding area. Nearly 30 volunteer interpreters, speaking dozens of languages, assist visitors who have questions on the convention, housing, restaurants, shopping, or any other questions they may have.

On-site Rental
Single-seat personal electric conveyance vehicles, specifically designed for those with disabilities, are allowed on the convention site and can also be rented via Vista Mobility Inc.* For more information on rentals, contact Vista Mobility Inc. at (877) 588-4782 ext. 2 or (262) 628-9655. Also allowed are Other Personal Disability Mobility Devices, such as Segways, when required because of the individual’s mobility disability and when operated in a safe manner, consistent with 28 C.F.R. 36.311(b)(1). Some of the grounds may be difficult for electric conveyance vehicles and wheelchairs to navigate, as they are grass- or gravel-covered.

* If special accessible transportation is required, please stop at the bus park area near the Main Admission Gate or call (920) 230-7932.

Restrooms
Multiple ADA accessible restrooms, hand washing stations, and showers designed for access by guests with mobility disabilities are available throughout the EAA grounds including Camp Scholler, convention grounds, and aircraft parking and camping.

ADA Accessible Ticket Counters
ADA accessible ticket counters are available for use in key locations around the grounds, including Main Gate Admissions, North 40, and camper and showplane registration.

Office:         262-628-9655 (Monday - Friday, 9 a.m. to 5 p.m.)

Toll Free:     1-877-588-4782 x2 (Monday - Friday, 9 a.m. to 5 p.m.)

NOTE: Individually owned or rented automobiles, motorcycles, mopeds, bicycles, and all-terrain vehicles are not recognized as authorized vehicles for guests with disabilities and are not allowed on the convention site.

items.title: Dorsal Fin to Avoid Loss-of-Control
items.html: The proposed method consists of a sharp-edged dorsal fin to be added in front of the vertical tail. Although this aerodynamic device is known by many, the exact physical workings of it are not always known and wide-spread implementation has never caught on. Currently there are no design methods for dorsal fins and the exact shape is normally determined during wind tunnel tests. This paper describes what a dorsal fin is used for, initial force derivation and CFD simulation results.

items.title: Hand Prop Your Aircraft
items.html:
"Prop it Right and Save a Life”

Greg and Cindy Heckman will demonstrate the Safe and Legal way to hand prop an aircraft engine.  Many Vintage aircraft must be started by hand propping since they may not have an electrical system for starting. In the past several years, we have taught well over a thousand people how to hand prop an aircraft engine safely here at Oshkosh. This program was started by the late Dale Gustafson, a long-time vintage aircraft judge, who saw the need since the emergence of the Sport Pilot License and the newly purchased older airplanes.   We miss Gus since he has Gone West in 2014.

items.title: Warbirds in Review F8F Bearcat
items.html:
Grumman F8F Bearcat owned by John O’ Connor. 

History comes to life through legendary wartime aircraft during Warbirds in Review sessions, which delve into aircraft restoration and operation and spotlight veterans sharing stories about what it was like to fly in combat or provide ground support. Presentations take place at 10 a.m. and 1 p.m. daily, July 24-29 on the Warbirds in Review ramp in Warbird Alley. The schedule also includes daily demonstrations at 9:30 a.m. and 12:30 p.m. from the Warbirds Living History Group on flight gear associated with the upcoming aircraft. Next, vocalist Theresa Eaman will entertain the crowds with tunes from the 1940's through the 1960's. Several Warbirds in Review presentations will be followed by book signing opportunities in the Warbirds Merchandise Building.

“July 2017 marks the 15th Anniversary of Warbirds in Review” said Connie Bowlin, EAA Warbirds of America president and Warbirds in Review program founder. “As I look back on the modest beginning thinking of Tex Hill, Bud Anderson, Robin Olds, Gunther Rall, Shorty Rankin, and so many other World War II, Korea, Vietnam, Gulf War, Afghanistan and current military veterans who have been a part of Warbirds in Review, it is humbling. What began with a simple idea, with a boom box and roll around stairs, to offer a time when people could come to hear an owner talk about their aircraft has become a truly world class program. With David Hartman as the writer and moderator, the award winning production crew of Sleeping Dog Productions, the support of Jim Hagedorn, Scotts Miracle Gro Company, Warbird members Ron and Diane Fagen, numerous other donors and the total support of aircraft owners, pilot and ground crew members, we have grown to a level beyond all expectations. The live streaming of Warbirds in Review in 2016 was viewed in 64 countries.  For me personally it is a little overwhelming to know that we have entertained and shared our history with the world.  With Jumbotron, bleachers, sound systems, worldwide live streaming and the participation of so many terrific Warbird members the evolution has exceeded all expectations.”

F8F Bearcat and Blue Angel F-18 – John O’Conner is the owner of the beautiful F8F Bearcat painted in the Blue Angel scheme.  We are confident that the Blue Angels will be a part of this presentation with one of the demo team pilots and the F-18 but that is subject to change. Regardless, this will be a tribute to the Navy featuring the F8F Bearcat.

items.title: Timeless Voices Tent, Warbirds
items.html:
EAA's Timeless Voices of Aviation oral history preservation program has been recording video interviews with military and civilian aviators since 2002. Visit the Timeless Voices Tent in the Warbirds area to schedule an interview to preserve your aviation story for future generations. Under the banner "Let No Story Go Untold," Timeless Voices of Aviation ensures that the first person oral histories of aviation’s development are preserved for future generations of family members, teachers, students, historians and others.

Pilots, aircrew, homebuilders, restorers, mechanics, air traffic controllers, air racers, designers - all are welcome to tell your story.

items.title: Design & Flight of a Turbojet Drone
items.html: This presentation will detail the design, integration, and flight testing of a turbojet-powered drone (N619RA). This autonomous 55-lb UAV, dubbed the Avanti, is capable of 200 KTAS and has triple-redundant radio links. The testing program for this unique vehicle will be detailed – including determination of maximum speed, range, and endurance. The reliability of the radio control link is also a key concern, since this aircraft is designed to fly over 10 nm from its control station.

items.title: Top 3 Causes of Damaging Vibration
items.html: Are moderate vibrations just something you should live with? The motor mounts are designed to absorb vibrations so what is the harm? Pilots often think that moderate to harsh vibrations in the powerplant are just a mild irritation with no long-term consequences. However, untreated vibration problems can lead to expensive repairs, dangerous exhaust leaks, and crew fatigue. Discover the top causes and effects of vibration in airplanes and learn how to accurately diagnose them.

items.title: Warbirds
items.html:
"Keep 'em Flying": That's the motto - and the mission - of EAA Warbirds of America, the EAA division that provides programs and services to those interested specifically in former military aircraft.

Seeing a warbird in a museum is a powerful thing, but to experience it with all of the senses is nothing short of awe-inspiring. To see it fly, to hear the roar of the engine and the whistling of the wind over the wings, and, most of all, to fly or even just ride in a warbird is a history lesson brought to life in the most exhilarating way imaginable. That experience reminds us of the sacrifices made by veterans who flew these aircraft in combat in order for us to enjoy the freedoms — not to mention the aircraft — we take for granted today.

Whether you fly, restore, or simply enjoy warbirds and their place in history, we invite you to consider adding Warbirds of America to your EAA membership.

items.title: Everything About Learning to Fly
items.html: Everything you wanted to know about learning to fly. This humorous and informative forum will provide answers to common myths about what it takes to get your pilot's certificate. Learn some ways to save money and time towards your dream of being a pilot.

items.title: Hypoxia/Carbon Monoxide Poisoning
items.html: As we ascend in altitude the available oxygen declines leading to hypoxia above 8000 feet AGL. Carbon Monoxide (CO) produces hypoxia by preventing the use of oxygen. The current technology of oxygen delivery systems and the monitoring and prevention of CO poisoning will be discussed.
